Let the side length of the square be $s.$  Then the vertices of the square are $(\pm s/\sqrt{2}, \pm s/\sqrt{2}).$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

draw(xscale(sqrt(3))*yscale(sqrt(6))*Circle((0,0),1));
draw((sqrt(2),sqrt(2))--(-sqrt(2),sqrt(2))--(-sqrt(2),-sqrt(2))--(sqrt(2),-sqrt(2))--cycle);
draw((-2,0)--(2,0));
draw((0,-3)--(0,3));
draw((sqrt(2),sqrt(2))--(sqrt(2),0));
draw((sqrt(2),0)--(0,0));
draw((0,0)--(0,sqrt(6)/sqrt(2)));
[/asy]

Then we must have
\[\left( \frac{s}{\sqrt{2}} \right)^2 \cdot \frac{1}{3} + \left( \frac{s}{\sqrt{2}} \right)^2 \cdot \frac{1}{6} = 1.\]Solving, we find $s = \sqrt{6}.$  Therefore, the area of the square is $\boxed{6}.$

The semi-axes of the ellipse are $\sqrt{3}$ and $\sqrt{6},$ so the semi-diagonal of the square is $\min(\sqrt{3},\sqrt{6}).$

[asy]
